Document: setting_up_xr
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/setting_up_xr.rst
Summary: Explains the recommended renderer choices for VR projects in Godot.
Godot has 3 renderer options for projects: Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+. The current recommendation is to use the Mobile renderer for any desktop VR project, and use the Compatibility renderer for any project running on a standalone headset like the Meta Quest 3. XR projects will run with the Forward+ renderer, but it isn't well optimized for XR right now compared to the other two.
---CHUNK---
Document: setting_up_xr
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/setting_up_xr.rst
Summary: This section explains how to enable and configure OpenXR support in Godot Engine project settings.
OpenXR is an industry standard for XR platforms, providing a standardized API for XR applications. It is maintained by the Khronos Group and integrates closely with Vulkan. OpenXR must be enabled when Godot starts, which is done by checking the `xr/openxr/enabled` setting in the project settings under **XR > OpenXR**.

Additional OpenXR settings are available in the same section, but they cannot be modified while the application is running. The default settings are suitable for initial setup. For detailed information on these settings, refer to the OpenXR settings documentation.

To enable XR shaders, navigate to **XR > Shaders** in the project settings and check the `shaders/enabled` box. After enabling shaders, click the **Save & Restart** button.

Warning: Many post-processing effects are not yet compatible with stereoscopic rendering and may cause issues if used.
---CHUNK---
Document: Setting up the XR scene
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/setting_up_xr.rst
Summary: This section describes the basic node setup required for an XR scene in Godot, including the XROrigin3D, XRCamera3D, and XRController3D nodes, and provides GDScript and C# code for initializing the OpenXR interface.

Every XR application needs at least an XROrigin3D and an XRCamera3D node. Most will have two XRController3D, one for the left hand and one for the right. The camera and controller nodes should be children of the origin node. Add these nodes to a new scene and rename the controller nodes to LeftHand and RightHand.

The warning icons are expected and should go away after you configure the controllers. Select the left hand and set it up as follows. And the right hand.

Right now all these nodes are on the floor; they will be positioned correctly at runtime. To help during development, it can be helpful to move the camera upwards so its y is set to 1.7, and move the controller nodes to -0.5, 1.0, -0.5 and 0.5, 1.0, -0.5 for respectively the left and right hand.

Next, add a script to the root node with the following code:

GDScript:
    extends Node3D

    var xr_interface: XRInterface

    func _ready():
        xr_interface = XRServer.find_interface("OpenXR")
        if xr_interface and xr_interface.is_initialized():
            print("OpenXR initialized successfully")

            # Turn off v-sync!
            DisplayServer.window_set_vsync_mode(DisplayServer.VSYNC_DISABLED)

            # Change our main viewport to output to the HMD
            get_viewport().use_xr = true
        else:
            print("OpenXR not initialized, please check if your headset is connected")

C#:
    using Godot;

    public partial class MyNode3D : Node3D
    {
        private XRInterface _xrInterface;

        public override void _Ready()
        {
            _xrInterface = XRServer.FindInterface("OpenXR");
            if(_xrInterface != null && _xrInterface.IsInitialized())
            {
                GD.Print("OpenXR initialized successfully");

                // Turn off v-sync!
                DisplayServer.WindowSetVsyncMode(DisplayServer.VSyncMode.Disabled);

                // Change our main viewport to output to the HMD
                GetViewport().UseXR = true;
            }
            else
            {
                GD.Print("OpenXR not initialized, please check if your headset is connected");
            }
        }
    }

This code fragment assumes we are using OpenXR; if you wish to use any of the other interfaces, you can change the find_interface call.

Warning: As you can see in the code snippet above, we turn off v-sync. When using OpenXR, you are outputting the rendering results to an HMD that often requires us to run at 90Hz or higher. If your monitor is a 60Hz monitor and v-sync is turned on, you will limit the output to 60 frames per second. XR interfaces like OpenXR perform their own sync. Also note that by default the physics engine runs at 60Hz as well, and this can result in choppy physics. You should set Engine.physics_ticks_per_second to a higher value.

If you run your project at this point, everything will work, but you will be in a dark world. To finish the starting point, add a DirectionalLight3D and a WorldEnvironment node to your scene. You may wish to also add a MeshInstance as a child to each controller node just to temporarily visualize them. Make sure you configure a sky in your world environment.

Now run your project; you should be floating somewhere in space and be able to look around.

Note: While traditional level switching can definitely be used with XR applications, where this scene setup is repeated in each level, most find it easier to set this up once and load levels as a subscene. If you do switch scenes and replicate the XR setup in each one, do make sure you do not run initialize multiple times. The effect can be unpredictable depending on the XR interface used. For the rest of this basic tutorial series, we will create a game that uses a single scene.